{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_cicerone_ver01/data/sn83016244/00271761302/1937120101/0519.xml":{"full_text":"Associated Press Day Wire\nService.\nFor 67 Years Devoted to the\nBest Interests of Key West\nVOLUME LV.III. No. 285.\nEnthusiasm Prevails At\nFellowship Gob Meeting\nCHAS. H. KETCHUM DE\nLIVERS AN ADDRESS\nCITING IDEALS OF\nTRUE AMERICANISM\n\"America is losing sight of the\nideals of true Americanism\",\nspeaker Chas. H. Ketchum stated\nin a stirring speech at a meeting\nof the Stone Church Service Club\nlast night.\nThis year marked great mile\nstones in American progress, with\nthe sesquicentennial celebration\nof the adoption of the Constitu\ntion, the centennial anniversary\nof the free public school system\nand Armistice day, Mr. Ketchum\nsaid, and yet there arc forces at\nwork within the country today\nwhich are going in a direction\naway from our American ideals\nof freedom of speech and religion,\nequality and justice to all. Such\nmovements are Communism and\nBolshevism.\nIn this year of our democracy,\ngreat problems have arisen which\nhave never been dealt with be\nfore. Social unrest is evident\namong a great number of the peo\nple of this country, especially in\nthe labor and capital clashes,\nclimaxed by sit-down strikes.\nIf every one in America aided\nthe government to the best of his\nability in these pressing problems,\nwe would not only safeguard Am\nerican ideals, we would soon solve\nour difficulties.\nMotion by Stephen Cochran\nSingleton to appoint a revolving\ncommittee to attend council meet\nings was passed. The committee\nis composed of Charles H. Ket\nchum, William Watkins, Fernando\nCamus and Prof. E. S. Waldron.\nCornTrmte*\nthe importance of the coming spe\ncial election on the bond refund\ning issue before the people of Key\nWest through its chairman,\nCharles Ketchum, reported that\nthe aid of the Chamber of Com\nmerce and individual members of\nthe Rotary Club had been enlist\ned and that a meeting to discuss\nplans will be held soon.\nA musical interlude was pre-|\nsen ted with violin selections by\nFred Knight, and Gerald Saun\nders; Kingman Curry at the\npiano.\nMembership in the Red Cross\nwas decided on at a previous,\nmeeting and a fund for toys for\npoor children was raised.\nA basketball team has been or\nganized and will be outfitted with\nuniforms and other equipment.\nGuests were Rev. Wm. J. Rea\ngan, Allan Armstrong, Dr. Fred\nCarbonell. Charles Yates and Les\nlie Russell.\nSTATE AUTO TAGS\nPLACED ON SALE\nState automobile tags went on\nsale this morning at the office of\nTax Collector Frank H. Ladd,\nwho purchased the first tag which\nwas Number 1. Number was\nsold to William Watkins, and\nNumber 3 went to Judge William\nV. Albury.\nThese tags carry the Monroe\nCounty Number 38, this county\nbeing Number 38 on the list, and\nincidentally the years\u2019 number. It\nis a very attractive tag, finished\nin black and yellow.\nCOUNTY BOARD\nMEETS TONIGHT\nRegular meeting of the board of\ncounty commissioners will he held\nat 8 o\u2019clock this evening* in the\noffice of Clerk Ross C. Sawyer in\nthe county court house.\nNothing other than the regular\nroutine business is schAluled fur\nconsideration it was announced\nby Chairman Bervaldi.\nSTEAL 4-ROOM HOUSE\nWalsenburg. Col.\u2014Police offi\ncers are searching for the thief,\nor thieves, who stole a 4-room\nhouse, complete with chimney\nand porch, which disappeared\nduring one night.\nELECTRICAL APPLIANCES MAKE WONDERFUL GIFTS. SEE OUR LARGE LINE BEFORE YOU BUY. SOUTH FLORIDA CONTR AND ENG. CO, PHONE 59$\nSllje IKctj West Citizen\nSAYS KEY WEST\nIS VERY ENTICING\n\"Key West is so much more\nenticing than other resorts\nthat all travelers should in\nclude the city in their iti\nnerary\". is |he opinion of Mrs.\nArthur M. Stowe who with\nMr. Stowe is on a visit here.\nThe couple have travelled\nover most of America and\nCanada and claim further\nthat America is a wonderful\ncountry in which to travel be\ncause of its variety.\nMr. Stowe is very much in\nterested in angling and in the\nexcellent fishing of these wa\nters. He is out in a party\nboat today.\nMr. and Mrs. Stowe winter\nat Mt. Dora. Florida, and\nsummer at Meredith, N. H.\nWASHINGTON NOTES\nANTI-LYNCHING BILL\nThe anti-lynching biy, accord\ning to some observers, is sure to\npass. A few commentators think\nthat it will be stymied. Opponents\ngenerally, are resigned to passage\nbut rely upon the Supreme Court\nto intervene.\nPOPULATION\nNext May, according to esti\nmates, the population of the\nUnited States will touch the 130,-\n000,000 mark. Statisticians say\nthat the total population of this\ncountry will not exceed 150,000,-'\n000. Incidentally, the birthrate\nwhich was 37 a thousand in the\nlast century, dropped to 16.8 in\n1935.\nREASSURING\nPh-ere reassuring fac\ntors in the present business situa\ntion. The banking system is not\nexpanded, interest rates are low,\nno volume of brokers\u2019 loans, no\noverdevelopment of capital in\ndustries, no export booms and no\ncredit shortage.\nWAGES AND HOURS\nProspects for passage of the\nwages and hours bill, bottled up\nin the house rules committee,\nwere not increased last week,\nwhen William of\nthe A. F. of L., demanded that it\nbe re-written to include \u201cspread\nthe work\u201d provisions and to elim\ninate a board to fix minimum\nwages and maximum hours.\nTHIRD TERM\nIt is reported that the President\nin a letter to Norman H. Davis,\nrecently made clear his intention\nto retire at the end of his present\nterm, saying he was beginning to\nfeci a. little tired and that by 1940\nhe expected to be anxious to go\nhome, conscious that he had done\nhis part\nDOUBTFUL\nContinued agitation demands a\nchange in the Neutrality law with\nmany proposals affecting the\npower of the President to embroil\nthis country in hostilities ready\nto be launched. It is doubtful if\nthere will be any extensive alter\nation of the present law at this\ntime, however.\nC. OF L.\nr he Federal Trade Commission\nis investigating the factors re\nsponsible for the rer\u2019it increased\ncost of living, which the Presi\ndent thinks may be attributable\nto \u201cmonopolistic practices and\nother unwholesome methods of\ncompetition.\u201d\nHOUSING\nNathan Straus. Administrator\nof the Federal Housing Author\nity, points out that it may lend\nas much as 90 percent of the\ncost of a project but states that\nthe local authority must provide\nthe remaining 10 percent. The\nrent necessary to pay operating\ncosts, plus retirement of the loan\nin 60 years, is determined along\nwith the rent that slum dwellers\nin the locality can afford to pay.\nIf there is a difference, then the\nlocality has to contribute 20 per\ncent of the subsidy necessary to\nmake the project succeed, with\nthe Government putting up the\nother 80 per cent. Local authori\nties may make their contributions\nin cash or tax exemption.\nARRANGE TOLL\nFOR AUTOS ON\nNEW SCHEDULE\nFIX PRICES TO BE CHARGED\nON FERRIES WHEN ROAD\nIS OPENED AS FAR DOWN\nAS HOG KEY\nCommittees from the County\nCommissioners and the Overseas\nRoad and Toll Bridge Commis\nsion, met last night for the pur\npose of agreeing on an equitable\ntoll rate to be put in effect at the\ntime the road is opened this\nmonth, the date of the opening to\nbe announced later.\nOf course, it was explained, this\ndoes not mean the entire high\nway, but only that portion from\nLower Matecumbe to Hog Key,\nwhich will mean that the approxi\nmate 13 miles from Hog Key to\nNo Name Key, will be travelled\nby ferry boat, as usual.\nThe agreement reached was\nthat the charges would be as fol\nlows: Cars up to 14 feet length,\n$2. Cars from 14 to 16 feet' in\nlength, $2.50. Cars beyond the\nlength of 16 feet, $3. For car and\na trailer, $7.50. Each passenger\nin car or trailer will be required\nto pay a charge of 25 cents.\nPresent at the meeting were\nCommissioners Wm. R. Porter and\nNorberg Thompson, the latter be\ning in charge of all ferry opera\ntions. Vice Chairman J. N. Cos\ntar, of the Overseas Road and\n101 l Bridge' Commission, Ralph\nBoyden, and C. C. Symonette,\nwho was chairman of the commit\ntee.\nCAPTAIN CARLSON\nDIES IN NORFOLK\nWAS FATHER OF MRS. H. S.\nDEXTER WHO FORMERLY\nRESIDED HERE\n(From Norfolk Ledger-Dispatch\nFuneral services for Captain\nCarlson, who died at his resi\ndence, 827 Camp avenue, Satur\nday morning, were conducted yes\nterday afternoon at 2 o\u2019clock at\nLeKies Methodist Church, of\nwhich he was an active member\nfor a number of years. The serv\nices were largely attended.\nRev. G. E. Hopkins, pastor, of\nficiated, assisted by the Rev. L.\nOakey Wilbem, former pastor.\nThere were many beautiful floral\nofferings, the casket being cover\ned with a double spjay of Easter\nlilies, roses and fern. During the\nservices thtT choir sang \u201cIn the\nSweet Bye and Bye,\u201d and Mrs.\nVera Windor sang \u201cSafe in the\nArms of Jesus,\u201d accompanied on\nthe organ by Mrs. F. M. Ambrose.\nHonorary pallbearers were\nCapt W. H. Lauder, Herman As\npergren, T. G. Rydingsvard, Capt.\nAnders Williams, F. K. Carlton,\nCapt John Johnson, Capt. J. M.\nLawrence, Capt. B. 0. Colonna,\nBraden Vanderventer. D. A. Kel\nsey, Arthur Jett, Dr. Bernard Par\nrish, Leon T. Seawell, J. P. Hop\nkins, Percy Stephenson, William\nGraham, and Capt. John Eth\neridge. Active pallbearers were\nPaul Holson, Charles M. Early, C.\nHerbert Simpson, Walter Mar\nshall, Capt. William Hogg, Capt.\nRufus L. Miles. H. P. Smith, and\nCapt H. F. Larimore.\nEditor's Note: Captain Carlson\nwas the father of Mrs. H. S. Dex\nter, whose husband was stationed\nhere as agent for the tug. War\nbler. of Merritt-Chapman-Seott,\nCorp. Captain Carlson spent a\nnumber of winters in Key West.\nMr. Dexter was transferred to\nNew York last year.\nTUG PIONEER\nARRIVES HERE\nTug Pioneer, of the Belcher Oil\nCos., of Miami, arrived this week\nand berthed at the main pier of\nthe Sam Anderson holdings, for\nmerly the Florida East Coast\nRailway.\nIn tow of the tug was a barge\nladen with oil to be pumped\nthrough the pipe lines of a local\ndistributing plant for one of the\nlarge oil companies.\nKEY WEST, FLORIDA, WEDNESDAY, DECEMBER 1, 1937.\nECONOMIC HIGHLIGHTS\nHappenings That Affect the Dinner Pails, Dividend\nChecks and Tax Bills of Every Individual; Na\ntional and International Problems Insep\narable From Local Welfare\nAs Congress settles down to\nwork, each branch has on its cal\nendar a sizable list of important\nlaws which were passed at the\nlast session by one of the Houses\nbut not by the other. The status\nof these bills is not changed by\nthe ending of the first session\u2014\nthey go over into the following\nsession on precisely the same ba\nsis as if Congress had not ad\njourned at all. Some of them will\ncome up in the current special\nsession\u2014those which do not, will\ncome again to prominence when\nthe regular, concluding session of\nthe 75th Congress is called in Jan\nuary. The United States News\nrecently published a summary qt\nthe more important acts which\nhave met the approval of one\nbranch, and are yet to be passed\no\"t condemned by the other.\nThe Senate, in its first session,\nI passed several extremely import\nant measures, which are now\nready for House of Representa\ntives\u2019 scrutiny. These bills are:\nWAGES AND HOURS: The\nbill creates a Federal Board with\nsweeping powers to establish\nmaximum hours of work and\nminimum wages, under certain\nrestrictions. It is an Administra\ntion \u201cmust\u201d measure, and was one\nof the two desired laws which led\nto the calling of the special ses\nsion. Chance for passage in pres\nent form is only fair; there is a\nbetter chance that extensive re\nvision will be demanded. Busi\nness sentiment is solidified\nagainst the bill, not, primarily,\nbecause of fear of the wages and\nhours standards it provides, but\nbecause of the feeling that the\nboard would be a czar over in\ndustry. The business recession,\nwhich has resulted in a strong de\nsire on the part of many congress\nmen to make the special and the\nnext regular session Reassuring\nto has damaged the\nbill\u2019s chances.\nCHILD LABOR: Will probably\npass, then become an issue in the\ncourts.\nWHEAT INSURANCE: Would\nset up a plan to protect farmers\nagainst wheat crop failures. Is\nhighly debatable as a practical\nmeasure, but has good chance of\npassing, perhaps in revised form.\nREVISION OF FOOD AND\nDRUGS LAW: Designed to cor\nrect weaknesses and inadequacies\nin the present law. Will probably\npass, though not without strong\nopposition.\nTRAIN LIMIT LAW: Would\nrestrict length of freight trains to\n70 cars. Is supported by labor as\na make-work measure, opposed\nby railway management on the|\ngrounds that its cost would be un\nbearable without major rate in\ncreases, and it would make opera\ntion lt?ss safe. House opposition\nto the law has been growing.\nChance of passing seems waning.\nCONDEMNATION OF SIT-\nSTART PAYMENT'\nOF POLL TAXES\nFOUR WERE ISSUED DURING\nMORNING FOR COMING\nSPECIAL ELECTION\nProspective voters at the\nspecial election to be held on\nDecember 30. are beginning to\nrealize that but a few more days\nare to pass, when the opportuni\nty for securing poll taxes will\nhave passed, as the last must be\nbought not later than the after\nnoon of Saturday. December 11.\nThe first thing which took\nplace this morning when the of\nfice of Tax Collector Frank H\nLadd was opened, was the en\ntrance of Chief Harry M Baker,\nof the Key W'est Fire Depart\nment. who made a payment for\ntwo poll taxes, one for himself\nand one for Mrs Baker.\nWithin a short time after that\nRev. Joe Tolle. pastor of First\nMi thodwt church, went into the\noffice, and he too secured two,\nc.ne for himself and one for Mrs\nTolle. No other sales were re\nported up to 2 30 o\u2019clock.\nDOWN STRIKES: This is not a\nlaw but an expression of congres\nsional sentiment on a major issue\nof the time. Has much better\nchance of passing the House now\nthan it did last session, but it may\nbe tabled and never brought to a\nvote as many members would pre\nfer to dodge the question.\nImportant laws passed by the\nHouse, and now on the Senate\nroster include:\nTHE ANTI-LYNCHING LAW:\nThis has been a burning topic for\nmany years, and at the opening of\nthe special session resulted in a\nvirtual filibuster by Southern\nmembers. Poor chance of passage\n\u2014i-Southern Senators feel it would\n(destroy the sovereignty of the\nslates, are prepared to talk it in\nto* oblivion whenever it appears.\n\u25a0REVISION OF BANKRUPTCY\nACT: Not a dramatic issue, has\nflood chance of passage.\nREGULATION OF NATURAL\n(JAS: Also has good chance of\npassage.\nPLACING POSTMASTERS\nUNDER CIVIL SERVICE STAT\nUS: Practically everyone agrees\nthis should be done\u2014but not\neveryone agrees the pending bill\nis the way to do it. Opponents\nsay the measure would give the\nAdministration a stranglehold on\nthe postmasters, and result in a\ntremendous political machine,\ni However, the chance for passage\n\u2022seems good.\nREPEAL OF SALARY PUBLI\ni CITY LAW: Top corporation sal\naries are now published periodic\nally by the SEC. Opponents say\nthis encourages blackmail, kid-!\nnapping, other crimes; is an un-\nwarranted invasion of private\nJ rights. Proponents say salary;\npublicity is necessary to protect\nj corporate stockholders from ex-\ncessive and unjustifiable execu- j\ntjve salaries. Chance of passage\nonly fair.\nREORGANIZATION OF FED-\nERAL DEPARTMENTS: Like\nthe civil service for postmasters\nbill, this measure is based on\nsomething that everyone feels is\nnecessary in the interest of gov\nernmental efficiency and econo\nmy\u2014but a great many people are\n\u2018opposed to the current proposal\nfor the reason that it would place\nthe independent .bureaus, such as\nthe FTC and ICC, under the Ex-\nI ecutive. Chance for passage fair, j\nThis does not exhaust the list\nof pending measures which have\npassed one branch, but it lists the\nmost important. It may be some\ntime, however, before most of\nthem are debated\u2014the business\nrecession has greatly changed the;\nlegislative outlook. A strong con\n[gressional bloc, led by prominent\n.Democrats, feels that Congress\nI should first deal with legislation\naffecting all business, such as the\nCapital Gains and Undistributed\nProfits Taxes, in an effort to stop 1\nthe declnie in production, employ\nment and earnings. j\nCHINESE PONT\nLIRE PROCRESS\nLOS ANGELES COLONY FEAR\nTHEY WILL HAVE TO\nSEEK NEW HOMES\n(Bj tuorlalril Prf*l\nLOS ANGELES, Dec I.\u2014Steel\nframework of the clock tower of\nthe new union railroad\nterminal rising 250 feet above the\nstreet, is a grim reminder to resi\ndents of Los Angeles\u2019 Chinatown\nthat in a very short time they will\nbe forced to seek new homes.\nThe Chinese district is being de\nmolished to make way for prog\nress\u2014for what the Chamber of\nCommerce contends is one of the\nmost important projects under\ntaken by Lea Angeles in years.\nBut to Lon Get Low', patriarchal\nChinese, who sits in the doorway\nof his tea shop puffing medita\ntively upon a long-stemmed pipe,\nit is not so good.\n\u201cMr dome Los Langk-s long\ntime ago,\u201d he says. \u201cStleet here\nvelly quiet\u2014ootelody blether Len\nGee Low\u2014all diffent now. Bang\nbang\u2014bang, all day. Just like\nwar in China. Plenty too much\nnotae.\u201d\nCommerce Body Hears From\nMany Prospective Visitors\nWho Plan Wintering Here\nMany More Men Called\nFor Work On Bridges\nRequisitions for workers on the,\nbridges received yesterday and\ntoday, call for men for service\non contracts of the S. J. Groves\nand Sons Cos., and the C. Y.\nThomason Construction Cos.\nFor the Groves Cos., at Contract!\nGRANDDAUGHTER OF SAM\nHOUSTON HERE FOR WINTER\nMargaret Bell Houston, grand\ndaughter of the famous governor\nof Texas, Sam Houston, and writ\ner of note, travelled over nearly\nall of Florida\u2019s coastline looking\nfor a locale for a coming novel\nbut was not satisfied until Mon\nday night when she arrived in\nKey West by bus and knew the\nIsland City to be exactly the\nplace she had in mind.\nThe quaintness, beauty, foreign\natmosphere and rocking fishing\nboat masts at the wharves all go\nto make up the location she has\nbeen searching for.\nMrs. Houston is the author of\nmany novels, serials, short stories;\nand poems. She has written of\nthe Creoles and Cajuns of Louisi\nana, of mountaineers and natives'\nNEWS NOTES\n\"NO STORM\" YEAR\"\nJacksonville. Fla.\u2014For the first\ntime in six years the United\nStates enjoyed a \u201cnon-hurricane\u201d\nyear, Senior Meteorologist Walter\nJ. Bennett, head of the special\nhurricane warning service, said\nthe season just ended was un\nusual in that not a single \u201cbig\nwind\u201d warning was posted and,\nfor the second consecutive year,\nthe Caribbean Sea was devoid of\nthese storms.\nBROKEN NOSE FIXED\nGarnett, Kan.\u2014Emerging from\na pile-up during a \u25a0football game,\nCapt. Lorimer McLaughlin of the\nGarnett High school team found\nhis nose broken. However, he\nstayed in the game and in a few\nminutes emerged from another\nscramble to find that someone had\nknocked it hack in place.\nESKIMOS FIGHT MUSK OXEN\ni Seattle. Wash.\u2014Musk oxen,\nbrought into Alaska by the U. S.\nBiological Survey to pr>vidi#the\nEskimos with food and wool, now\nthreaten to exterminate them.\nThe animals are overrunning the\nvillages and killing the Eskimo\u2019s\ndogs.\nDEAR DEER\nAshland. Wis.\u2014Several weeks\nago I B. Iverson ran into a deer\nwhich dashed across a highway.\nA garage repaired a damaged\nheadlight and fender. A few\nnights later Iverson\u2019s wife drove\nalong a forest-bordered highway.\nA deer darted out and crashed in\nto the automobile. The garag*-\nrepaired the same headlight and\nfender.\nOPERATES. DIES\nBaltimore, Md\u2014 While assisting,'\ntn a tonsil operation. Dr Charles;\nA Holland. 80, suffered a heart\nattack and dropped dead.\nMAILS CARD IN FIRE BOX\nYoungstown. Ohio\u2014Answering\na fire alarm, firemen f*und Nick\nYavarick. with the door of the\nalarm box open, trying desperate\nly to mail his unemployment cen\nsus questionnaire.\nSIX DT T IJI FIRE\nFort Collin*. Colo\u2014The expto-\nsfcm of an oil stove, which was\nused to warm the one-room shed'\nD., Marathon, a request is made\nfor six white and three colored\nlaborers, and for Contract F., one\nelectric welder.\nThe Thomason Cos., at Conch\nKey, Contract 8., asks for 12\nnegro laborers, four truck dri\nvers, and four air drill operators.\nI of the deep south, all with a light\nromantic touch.\nj Her most recently published\nnovel is \u201cWindow in Heaven\u201d,\nwhich ran serially in Good House\nkeeping magazine. \u201cGypsy Weath\ner,\u201d \u201cThe Little Straw Wife,\u201d\n\u201cThe Witch Man,\u201d \u201cMoon of De\nlight,\u201d \u201cHurdy-Gurdy\u201d and \u201cMag\nj ic Valley\u201d are among her other\nnovels.\nKatrina Houston, daughter of\nMrs. Houston, is with her mother\non this trip. She is a portrait art\nist. A self-portrait, which was\ndone with the aid of mirrors, a\ni most difficult piece of work, is an\ni excellent creation.\nMrs. Houston and Katrina are\nvery proud of their family name\nand are known legally by it\nThey are very enthusiastic over\nKey West and will remain here\ntor the winter season/\nin which Thomas CeCtt% his wife*\nand four members uf faming\nlived, is thotlght to\u2019hlvd sel fin!\nto the shack, burning ail of\n'to death.\nTEAM PADDLES COACH\nFlagstaff, Ariz.\u2014Reversing a\nj ruling made by their football\nI coach that any player who drew\nIa penalty could be paddled by the\ncach. the team exercised the\nsame privilege and paddled the\ncoach, Garrett Arbelbide, when\nthe team was penalized because\nArbelbide coached from the side\nlines.\n\nTOO LATE FOR FUNERAL\nlx>ndon.\u2014Ernest F. Bennett, 46-\nj year-old inventor, arrived in\nshoreham. Sussex, his home town,\nto discover that \u201che\u201d had drowned\nm the River Adur and had been\nburied. So closely did the drown\n,ed man resemble Bennett that\nfriends who saw the body at the\nmortuary, and even a doctor who\nhad treated him. were prepared to\nswear that it was he.\nLUCKYI\nNew York. When her gas\nrange exploded, her kitchen de\n-1 mnlished, a nearby china closet\nwrecked, two windows in the\nkitchen blown out. Mr* Elizabeth\nSullivan. 38. who was standing by\nthe stove, suffered only singed\neyebrow*.\nRELICS TO BE SOLD\nPhiiailelphia.\u2014The equipment\nThomas A. Edison used fifty-four\nyears ago to introduce commercial\nelectricity to a skeptical world\ntwo genefatpf* and an unwieldly\nI engine\u2014yr*7l go on the auction\nW** on DwipUr 21\nFALL FATAL\nBaltaeore. Md.\u2014A fail down\nthe ftairr of her home proved fat\nal to Mrs. Rose Karker, 87. who\ndied in a hospital of a fractured\nskull and internal injuries.\nBIG FREE DANCE\nPENA\u2019S GARDEN OF ROSES\nTomorrow If to hi. II till\nM*ic By\nJofca Pritchard\u2019s Orchestra\ni\nKey West, Florid*, hme the\nmost equable climate in tke\ncountry; with an average\nrange of only 14* Fahrenheit\nPRICE FIVE CENTS\nLETTERS RECEIVED INDI\nCATE THAT ISLAND\nCITY OFFERS CHARM\nTO OUTSIDERS\nKay West Chamber of Com\nmerce continues its work of build\ning friendly contacts with what\nSecretary S. C. Singleton calls\n\"that country lying north of us.\nknown as the United States,\nwhich is entitled to our sympathy\ndue to its misfortune of being\nisolated from Key West\"\nThis statement was made yes\nterday after The Citizen had been\ninvited to look over the morning\nmail at the chamber as it was be\ning opened, and finding such\nphrases as the following from\nPortland, Maine. \"It sounds de\nlightful, and it appeals to me so\ncially and financially. I expect\nto arrive in about two weeks and\nstay until May.\"\nFrom Bridgeport, Connecticut,\nprospective visitor writes: \u201cFirst\nlet me ssy that aside from the\ncharm of your community, as de\nscribed in die circulars you kind\nly forwarded to me. your cordial\nand friendly note of November 6\nwould in itself cause me to visit a\nchap, who can wtite such a de\nl^ful\nAhotncr correspondent from\nI.afaydtii/lndi*na, writes: \"The\ndata yb mbited me is quite com\nplete and 1 am glad to learn that\nSfia\ntrie* jl h?i v< Avoided \u2022South Flor\nida lot the (test two Wesson* oh\nthis 'account, and 1 Will do ife fa\nQF T 7 i\nf Mia String 0 Putnam Wikofc\nwrites that her article \u201cWhat\u2019s\nBelow Miami\u201d will appear in the\nDecember 18 issue of Colliers un\nder the title \u201cSouth From Mi\nami\u201d, and adds \u201cI hope my story\nwill please you and all my other\ngood friends in Key West.\"\nFrom Anton Fisher, illustrator\nwho won the acclaim of many\nKey Westers by his beautiful full\npage color illustrations, in the\nSaturday Evening Post, comes the\nwelcome news that he will be lo\ncated in Key West this winter.\nAmong the interesting visitors\nat the offices yesterday were: Mrs.\nMargaret Bell Houston, and her\nI daughter Miss Katrina Houston.\n!of New York. Mrs Houston is a\nlineal descendant of General Sam\nHouston, and author of the aerial\n\u2018Windows in Heaven\u201d which was\na leading feature in \u201cGood House\nkeeping\" Looking over Florida\nfor the most colorful location for\na writer of stories. Mrs. Houston\nhas found in Kay Wad just what\nshe was looking for, and will be\nin the city for the season.\nCUBA ARRIVES\nFROMHAVANA\nVESSEL LEFT LATE Of ATTEN\nNOON CN ROUTE TO\nTAMPA\nSteamship Cute. af the P. Mid\nO S Company. arrived from\nHaviaa ynlitMjr tftmimn with\nno* fmt and three weood cabin\nfor Key Weal; 21 first\ncabin and no second* for Tamp*.\nKey W*l arrivals Armando\nPerez. Dolores Cervantes. Hunter\nSmith. William Tertmne.\nItems of the ship's manifest\ndimnd four tons of freight and\nthree lacks <A mad for Key West;\n32 tons of freight and ISO sacks ef\nmail fer Tamp*\nPnmgan boohing paeaege\nfrom Key West were Mina ftuby\nColeman. Sftas R Hashtna. H*in\nter Smith and fm. Tertume and\nan era* aeoaad caom.","height":"24960","width":"19740"}}
